pe":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Age less than 25 years","Polycystic ovary syndrome","Previous low birthweight infant","First-degree relative with type 2 diabetes","Body mass index less than 25 kg/m\u00b2"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors for gestational diabetes include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolycystic ovary syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E - Associated with insulin resistance which increases risk of gestational diabetes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge less than 25 years\u003C/strong\u003E - Advanced maternal age (\u0026gt;35 years) increases risk, not younger age\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrevious low birthweight infant\u003C/strong\u003E - Previous macrosomic baby (\u0026gt;4kg) increases risk, not low birthweight\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst-degree relative with type 2 diabetes\u003C/strong\u003E - While this is a risk factor, it is not as strongly associated as PCOS\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBody mass index less than 25 kg/m\u00b2\u003C/strong\u003E - Higher BMI increases risk, not lower BMI\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther important risk factors include previous gestational diabetes, certain ethnicities (South Asian, Middle Eastern, Pacific Islander), and multiple pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Polycystic ovary syndrome increases the risk of gestational diabetes due to underlying insulin resistance","Advanced maternal age, high BMI, and family history of diabetes are key risk factors for gestational diabetes","Previous gestational diabetes or macrosomic baby increases the risk in subsequent pregnancies"],"references":["Plows JF, Stanley JL, Baker PN, Reynolds CM, Vickers MH. The Pathophysiology of Gestational Diabetes Mellitus. Int J Mol Sci. 2018 Oct 26;19(11):3342. doi: 10.3390/ijms19113342. PMID: 30373146; PMCID: PMC6274679.","